## 1. Course description 🟢

This course introduces students to the full lifecycle of big data analytics, from data ingestion and storage to processing, modelling, visualisation, and interpretation. Students learn to work with large-scale datasets using modern tools and platforms, focus on practical analytics workflows, and develop skills needed for data-driven decision-making in intelligent systems and industry applications.

---

## 2. Course content (units & weightage) 🟢

| Unit | Syllabus | Weightage |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Big Data ecosystem and data platforms — characteristics of big data, volume, velocity, variety, veracity; Hadoop ecosystem overview; distributed storage; data lakes; basic cloud-based storage concepts. | 25 Marks |
| 2 | Data processing and analytics frameworks — batch and stream processing; MapReduce-style thinking; Spark fundamentals; transformations and actions; SQL-on-big-data concepts. | 25 Marks |
| 3 | Data modelling, warehousing and analytics pipelines — data warehouses, schema design, ETL/ELT, data quality, partitioning, indexing, performance tuning. | 25 Marks |
| 4 | Visualization, interpretation and governance — dashboards, visual storytelling, anomaly detection, privacy, security, ethical use of analytics, and reporting for decision support. | 25 Marks |

---

## 3. 🔵 Dual-level scope of each unit (KEYSTONE)

| Unit | Awareness level — every student must reach (the floor) | Advanced level — required to exceed 8 CGPA (the ceiling) |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Explain the characteristics of big data and identify common storage architectures such as distributed file systems and data lakes; describe the role of the Hadoop ecosystem and basic cloud storage services. | Compare distributed storage designs for a novel dataset and justify the choice of storage and processing approach for scale, latency, and cost. |
| 2 | Apply a basic batch or stream processing workflow to a provided dataset; perform transformations, aggregations, and simple analytics using a big-data framework. | Design an optimized processing pipeline for a real-world problem, including partitioning, caching, incremental computation, and performance trade-offs. |
| 3 | Build a simple analytics pipeline, explain schema choices, and perform data quality checks and basic performance tuning. | Design a scalable warehouse or lakehouse-style solution, justify modelling choices, and evaluate quality, lineage, and reliability concerns for larger workloads. |
| 4 | Create a basic dashboard or analytical report and explain key insights from data. | Produce an end-to-end analytics story with visualisation design, anomaly interpretation, governance controls, and ethical considerations for decision making. |

